00:54:33,770 --> 00:54:36,897
...then he laughed
and actually shook Andy's hand.

743
00:54:37,357 --> 00:54:39,692
- My ass!
BROOKS: Shook his hand.

744
00:54:39,859 --> 00:54:42,736
I tell you, I near soiled myself!

745
00:54:42,946 --> 00:54:47,199
All he needed was a suit and tie
and a jiggly hula gal on his desk...

746
00:54:47,409 --> 00:54:50,035
...he'd have been
"Mr. Dufresne," if you please.

747
00:54:50,203 --> 00:54:51,870
Making a few friends, huh, Andy?

748
00:54:53,164 --> 00:54:54,832
I wouldn't say "friends."

749
00:54:55,041 --> 00:54:58,877
I'm a convicted murderer
who provides sound financial planning.

750
00:54:59,045 --> 00:55:01,380
It's a wonderful pet to have.

751
00:55:01,589 --> 00:55:03,382
Got you out of the laundry, though.

752
00:55:03,925 --> 00:55:05,843
It might do more than that.

753
00:55:06,052 --> 00:55:08,762
How about expanding the library.
Get some new books.

754
00:55:08,972 --> 00:55:11,557
If you ask for something,
ask for a pool table.

755
00:55:12,309 --> 00:55:16,270
- Right.
- How do you expect to do that? I mean...

756
00:55:16,479 --> 00:55:19,440
...get new books in here,
"Mr. Dufresne, if you please."

757
00:55:19,899 --> 00:55:21,400
I'll ask the warden for funds.

758
00:55:21,568 --> 00:55:22,693
[MEN CHUCKLING]

759
00:55:22,861 --> 00:55:27,114
Son, son, son, six wardens have been
through here in my tenure, and I've learned...

760
00:55:27,365 --> 00:55:29,742
...one immutable, universal truth:

761
00:55:29,909 --> 00:55:32,202
Not one of them born whose asshole...

762
00:55:32,370 --> 00:55:36,415
...wouldn't pucker up tighter than
a snare drum when you ask for funds.

763
00:55:37,292 --> 00:55:40,210
- The budget's stretched thin as it is.
- I see.

764
00:55:40,420 --> 00:55:43,839
Perhaps I could write the state senate
and request funds directly from them.

765
00:55:44,049 --> 00:55:48,135
They have only three ways to spend
the taxpayers' money for prisons:

766
00:55:48,345 --> 00:55:50,763
More walls, more bars, more guards.

767
00:55:50,972 --> 00:55:53,640
Still, I'd like to try, with permission.
A letter a week.

768
00:55:53,850 --> 00:55:56,602
- They can't ignore me forever.
- Sure can.

769
00:55:56,853 --> 00:55:59,521
But you write your letters
if it makes you happy.

770
00:55:59,814 --> 00:56:02,441
I'll even mail them for you. How's that?

771
00:56:04,110 --> 00:56:06,904
RED: So Andy started writing
a letter a week...

772
00:56:07,113 --> 00:56:08,697
...just like he said.

773
00:56:12,869 --> 00:56:15,496
And, just like Norton said...

774
00:56:15,705 --> 00:56:17,164
...Andy got no answers.

775
00:56:25,382 --> 00:56:30,302
The following April, Andy did tax returns
for half the guards at Shawshank.

776
00:56:31,638 --> 00:56:33,889
Year after that, he did them all...

777
00:56:34,140 --> 00:56:36,058
...including the warden's.

778
00:56:37,811 --> 00:56:41,271
Year after that,
they rescheduled the intramural season...

779
00:56:41,481 --> 00:56:43,899
...to coincide with tax season.

780
00:56:45,485 --> 00:56:49,947
The guards on the opposing teams
all remembered to bring their W-2s.

781
00:56:50,156 --> 00:56:53,951
So Moresby Prison issued you a gun,
but you actually paid for it.

782
00:56:54,160 --> 00:56:55,869
Damn right. The holster too.

783
00:56:56,079 --> 00:56:58,539
See, that's tax-deductible.
You can write that off.

784
00:56:58,748 --> 00:57:01,792
RED: Yes, sir.
Andy was a regular cottage industry.

785
00:57:02,502 --> 00:57:07,005
In fact, it got so busy at tax time,
he was allowed a staff.

786
00:57:07,257 --> 00:57:09,716
Could you hand me
a stack of 1040s?

787
00:57:09,926 --> 00:57:14,763
RED: Got me out ofthe wood shop
a month out of the year, and that was fine.

788
00:57:16,015 --> 00:57:19,184
And still, he kept sending those letters.

789
00:57:22,939 --> 00:57:25,774
Red. Red. Andy.

790
00:57:25,942 --> 00:57:26,984
It's Brooks.

791
00:57:28,111 --> 00:57:29,611
RED:
Watch the door.

792
00:57:29,863 --> 00:57:31,196
Please, Brooks.

793
00:57:31,364 --> 00:57:33,240
- Calm the fuck down.
- Stay back!

794
00:57:33,700 --> 00:57:35,826
- Stay back, goddamn it!
- What's going on?

795
00:57:35,994 --> 00:57:39,037
You tell me. One second he's fine,
then out come the knife.

796
00:57:39,205 --> 00:57:41,081
Brooks. We can talk about this, right?

797
00:57:41,249 --> 00:57:45,085
There's nothing to talk about.
I'll cut his fucking throat.

798
00:57:45,378 --> 00:57:47,087
What's he done to you?

799
00:57:47,297 --> 00:57:48,964
It's what they done!

800
00:57:49,466 --> 00:57:50,716
I got no choice.

801
00:57:51,217 --> 00:57:53,510
Brooks, you won't hurt Heywood.
We all know that.

802
00:57:53,720 --> 00:57:56,180
- Right, Heywood?
- Sure. I know that.

803
00:57:56,389 --> 00:57:59,725
He's a friend of yours,
and Brooks is a reasonable man.

804
00:57:59,893 --> 00:58:01,894
- Right, guys?
- Yes.

805
00:58:02,061 --> 00:58:04,563
So put the knife down.
Brooks, look at me.

806
00:58:04,731 --> 00:58:08,734
Put the knife down. Brooks.

807
00:58:08,985 --> 00:58:11,069
Look at his neck, for God's sake.

808
00:58:11,821 --> 00:58:14,156
Look at his neck. He's bleeding.

809
00:58:15,074 --> 00:58:16,533
It's the only...

810
00:58:16,743 --> 00:58:18,785
It's the only way they'd let me stay.

811
00:58:19,078 --> 00:58:21,413
Come on, this is crazy.
You don't want to do this.

812
00:58:21,664 --> 00:58:23,749
Put it... Put it down.

813
00:58:23,958 --> 00:58:27,211
[SOBBING]

814
00:58:31,090 --> 00:58:34,009
Hey. Hey. Take it easy.

815
00:58:34,677 --> 00:58:36,261
You'll be all right.

816
00:58:36,429 --> 00:58:38,889
Him? What about me?

817
00:58:39,098 --> 00:58:41,475
Crazy old fool damn near cut my throat!

818
00:58:41,684 --> 00:58:43,602
RED:
You've had worse from shaving.

819
00:58:43,770 --> 00:58:45,521
What did you do to set him off?

820
00:58:45,688 --> 00:58:48,315
Nothing. I come in here to say farewell.

821
00:58:48,942 --> 00:58:51,610
Ain't you heard?
His parole's come through.

822
00:58:53,780 --> 00:58:56,740
I just don't understand
what happened in there, that's all.

823
00:58:56,908 --> 00:58:59,743
Old man's crazy as a rat
in a tin shithouse.

824
00:58:59,953 --> 00:59:01,828
Oh, Heywood, that's enough out of you.

825
00:59:02,038 --> 00:59:04,790
- Heard he had you shitting in your pants.
HEYWOOD: Fuck you.

826
00:59:05,041 --> 00:59:06,250
Knock it off.

827
00:59:07,210 --> 00:59:08,627
Brooks ain't no bug.

828
00:59:08,962 --> 00:59:10,629
He's just...

829
00:59:12,465 --> 00:59:14,258
He's just institutionalized.

830
00:59:15,635 --> 00:59:17,553
"Institutionalized," my ass.

831
00:59:17,762 --> 00:59:21,765
The man's been in here 50 years,
Heywood, 50 years!

832
00:59:21,975 --> 00:59:23,684
This is all he knows.

833
00:59:23,893 --> 00:59:26,186
In here, he's an important man...

834
00:59:26,396 --> 00:59:27,479
...an educated man.

835
00:59:28,314 --> 00:59:30,232
Outside, he's nothing.

836
00:59:31,109 --> 00:59:34,611
Just a used-up con
with arthritis in both hands.

837
00:59:34,821 --> 00:59:37,823
Probably couldn't get a library card
if he tried.

838
00:59:38,074 --> 00:59:39,825
You know what I'm trying to say?

839
00:59:40,076 --> 00:59:42,995
I do believe
you're talking out of your ass.

840
00:59:44,247 --> 00:59:46,498
You believe whatever you want.

841
00:59:47,083 --> 00:59:49,501
But I tell you these walls are funny.

842
00:59:51,087 --> 00:59:52,754
First you hate them.

843
00:59:54,591 --> 00:59:56,508
Then you get used to them.

844
00:59:58,428 --> 01:00:00,429
Enough time passes...

845
01:00:01,097 --> 01:00:03,098
...you get so you depend on them.

846
01:00:04,100 --> 01:00:06,310
That's "institutionalized."

847
01:00:06,519 --> 01:00:10,772
- Shit. I could never get like that.
- Oh, yeah?

848
01:00:11,649 --> 01:00:14,151
Wait till you've been here
as long as Brooks.

849
01:00:14,360 --> 01:00:15,944
Goddamn right.

850
01:00:18,531 --> 01:00:20,449
They send you here for life...

851
01:00:21,117 --> 01:00:23,452
...that's exactly what they take.

852
01:00:25,204 --> 01:00:27,205
Part that counts, anyway.

853
01:00:28,875 --> 01:00:31,501
[JAKE CROWING]

854
01:00:34,797 --> 01:00:37,716
I can't take care of you no more, Jake.

855
01:00:38,885 --> 01:00:40,552
You go on now.

856
01:00:41,804 --> 01:00:46,141
You're free.

857
01:01:02,450 --> 01:01:04,993
Bye. Joe?

858
01:01:05,161 --> 01:01:06,828
GUARD:
Good luck, Brooksie.

859
01:01:09,123 --> 01:01:11,208
Take care of yourself, Brooks.

860
01:01:44,784 --> 01:01:46,284
BROOKS:
Dear fellas:

861
01:01:46,577 --> 01:01:50,789
I can't believe how fast things move
on the outside.

862
01:01:52,083 --> 01:01:54,751
MAN:
Watch it, old-timer! Want to get killed?

863
01:01:55,962 --> 01:01:59,464
BROOKS: I saw an automobile once
when I was a kid...

864
01:02:00,133 --> 01:02:02,551
...but now they're everywhere.

865
01:02:06,222 --> 01:02:10,517
The world went and got itself
in a big damn hurry.

866
01:02:26,325 --> 01:02:30,120
The parole board
got me into this halfway house...

867
01:02:30,413 --> 01:02:32,080
...called "The Brewer"...

868
01:02:32,290 --> 01:02:33,457
...and a job...

869
01:02:33,666 --> 01:02:36,626
...bagging groceries at the Food-Way.

870
01:02:38,171 --> 01:02:40,589
It's hard work and I try to keep up...

871
01:02:40,798 --> 01:02:43,175
...but my hands hurt most of the time.

872
01:02:43,468 --> 01:02:48,346
Make sure your man double-bags.
Last time, the bottom near came out.

873
01:02:48,514 --> 01:02:51,266
Make sure you double-bag
like the lady says. Understand?

874
01:02:51,476 --> 01:02:52,851
Yes, sir. Surely will.

875
01:02:53,019 --> 01:02:56,563
BROOKS: I don't think the store manager
likes me very much.

876
01:02:59,567 --> 01:03:03,862
Sometimes after work,
I go to the park and feed the birds.

877
01:03:04,322 --> 01:03:05,822
I keep thinking...

878
01:03:06,032 --> 01:03:09,367
...Jake might just show up
and say hello.

879
01:03:09,994 --> 01:03:11,995
But he never does.

880
01:03:13,206 --> 01:03:18,043
I hope, wherever he is, he's doing okay
and making new friends.

881
01:03:21,672 --> 01:03:24,382
I have trouble sleeping at night.

882
01:03:24,717 --> 01:03:27,969
I have bad dreams, like I'm falling.

883
01:03:28,221 --> 01:03:30,472
I wake up scared.

884
01:03:30,681 --> 01:03:34,893
Sometimes it takes me a while
to remember where I am.

885
01:03:36,395 --> 01:03:41,316
Maybe I should get me a gun and rob
the Food-Way so they'd send me home.

886
01:03:41,609 --> 01:03:45,946
I could shoot the manager while
I was at it. Sort of like a bonus.

887
01:03:47,615 --> 01:03:51,618
I guess I'm too old
for that sort of nonsense anymore.

888
01:03:51,869 --> 01:03:53,578
I don't like it here.

889
01:03:53,788 --> 01:03:57,791
I'm tired of being afraid all the time.
I've decided...

890
01:03:58,626 --> 01:04:00,293
...not to stay.

891
01:04:11,222 --> 01:04:13,765
I doubt they'll kick up any fuss...

892
01:04:13,975 --> 01:04:17,477
...not for an old crook like me.

893
01:05:19,957 --> 01:05:24,210
ANDY: "I doubt they'll kick up any fuss,
not for an old crook like me.

894
01:05:25,254 --> 01:05:29,090
P.S. Tell Heywood I'm sorry
I put a knife to his throat.

895
01:05:29,300 --> 01:05:31,635
No hard feelings. Brooks."

896
01:05:42,104 --> 01:05:44,064
He should have died in here.

897
01:05:49,612 --> 01:05:51,029
HADLEY:
What the fuck have you done?

898
01:05:51,197 --> 01:05:53,865
It's a goddamn mess,
I'll tell you that.

899
01:05:59,413 --> 01:06:03,166
- What's all this?
- You tell me. They're addressed to you.

900
01:06:04,418 --> 01:06:05,752
Take it.

901
01:06:14,303 --> 01:06:15,804
"Dear Mr. Dufresne:

902
01:06:16,931 --> 01:06:18,890
In response to your repeated inquiries...

903
01:06:19,100 --> 01:06:23,395
...the state has allocated the enclosed
funds for your library project."

904
01:06:24,146 --> 01:06:25,981
This is $200.

905
01:06:26,190 --> 01:06:30,193
"In addition, the library district
has generously responded...

906
01:06:30,403 --> 01:06:32,946
...with a donation of used books
and sundries.

907
01:06:33,155 --> 01:06:37,283
We trust this will fill your needs.
We now consider the matter closed.

908
01:06:37,493 --> 01:06:39,369
Please stop sending us letters."

909
01:06:39,537 --> 01:06:42,205
I want all this cleared out
before the warden gets back.

910
01:06:42,415 --> 01:06:43,581
Yes, sir.

911
01:06:47,878 --> 01:06:49,045
Good for you, Andy.

912
01:06:51,841 --> 01:06:53,258
Wow.

913
01:06:54,343 --> 01:06:56,261
It only took six years.

914
01:06:57,847 --> 01:07:00,598
From now on, I'll write two
letters a week instead of one.

915
01:07:00,766 --> 01:07:04,102
I believe you're crazy enough.
Get this stuff out...

916
01:07:04,395 --> 01:07:06,813
...like he said.
I've got to pinch a loaf.

917
01:07:07,023 --> 01:07:08,481
When I come back...

918
01:07:08,691 --> 01:07:10,442
...this is all gone, all right?

919
01:07:46,645 --> 01:07:50,440
[ARIA FROM "THE MARRIAGE OF FIGARO"
PLAYS ON RECORD PLAYER]

920
01:07:59,200 --> 01:08:00,617
Do you hear that?

921
01:08:33,275 --> 01:08:36,528
[SCREECHING]

922
01:09:08,435 --> 01:09:09,435
[KNOCKING]

923
01:09:09,603 --> 01:09:12,814
GUARD:
Dufresne! Dufresne!

924
01:09:13,065 --> 01:09:14,566
Andy, let me out!

925
01:09:21,448 --> 01:09:26,411
RED: I have no idea to this day what those
two Italian ladies were singing about.

926
01:09:26,704 --> 01:09:28,913
Truth is, I don't want to know.

927
01:09:29,123 --> 01:09:31,624
Some things are best left unsaid.

928
01:09:35,212 --> 01:09:37,922
I like to think it was something
so beautiful...

929
01:09:38,132 --> 01:09:40,258
...it can't be expressed in words...

930
01:09:40,467 --> 01:09:43,386
...and makes your heart ache
because of it.

931
01:09:45,055 --> 01:09:47,557
I tell you, those voices soared...

932
01:09:47,808 --> 01:09:52,103
...higher and farther than anybody
in a gray place dares to dream.

933
01:09:52,313 --> 01:09:55,690
It was like a beautiful bird
flapped into our drab cage...

934
01:09:55,900 --> 01:09:58,651
...and made those walls dissolve away.

935
01:09:59,111 --> 01:10:01,279
And for the briefest of moments...

936
01:10:01,488 --> 01:10:04,490
...every last man at Shawshank felt free.

937
01:10:07,077 --> 01:10:09,746
It pissed the warden off
something awful.

938
01:10:11,040 --> 01:10:12,040
Open the door.

939
01:10:14,960 --> 01:10:16,711
Open it up!

940
01:10:18,005 --> 01:10:20,757
Dufresne, open this door!

941
01:10:22,092 --> 01:10:23,301
Turn that off!

942
01:10:30,351 --> 01:10:32,810
I am warning you. Turn that off!

943
01:10:46,659 --> 01:10:48,576
Dufresne.

944
01:10:50,537 --> 01:10:52,080
You're mine now.

945
01:10:59,505 --> 01:11:02,757
RED: Andy got two weeks in the hole
for that little stunt.

946
01:11:02,967 --> 01:11:04,550
HADLEY:
On your feet.

947
01:11:05,719 --> 01:11:08,137
JIGGER: Hey, look who's here.
SNOOZE: Maestro!

948
01:11:08,305 --> 01:11:09,514
Hey.

949
01:11:09,890 --> 01:11:13,559
You couldn't play something good, huh?
Like Hank Williams?

950
01:11:13,894 --> 01:11:16,688
They broke the door down
before I could take requests.

951
01:11:16,897 --> 01:11:20,024
- Was it worth two weeks?
- Easiest time I ever did.

952
01:11:20,234 --> 01:11:22,568
No such thing as easy time in the hole.

953
01:11:22,736 --> 01:11:24,445
JIGGER:
A week in the hole is like a year.

954
01:11:24,655 --> 01:11:27,949
SNOOZE: Damn straight.
- I had Mr. Mozart to keep me company.

955
01:11:28,158 --> 01:11:31,119
So they let you tote
that record player down there, huh?

956
01:11:33,539 --> 01:11:34,914
It was in here.

957
01:11:35,749 --> 01:11:37,000
In here.

958
01:11:38,127 --> 01:11:40,211
That's the beauty of music. They...

959
01:11:40,421 --> 01:11:42,755
...can't get that from you.

960
01:11:46,302 --> 01:11:48,678
Haven't you ever felt
that way about music?

961
01:11:50,472 --> 01:11:53,599
Well, I played a mean harmonica
as a younger man.

962
01:11:54,643 --> 01:11:56,352
Lost interest in it, though.

963
01:11:56,562 --> 01:11:58,146
Didn't make much sense in here.

964
01:11:58,480 --> 01:12:00,481
ANDY:
Here's where it makes the most sense.

965
01:12:01,025 --> 01:12:03,067
You need it so you don't forget.

966
01:12:03,652 --> 01:12:04,944
Forget?

967
01:12:05,237 --> 01:12:08,323
Forget that there are...

968
01:12:08,532 --> 01:12:09,949
...places...

969
01:12:10,451 --> 01:12:14,287
...in the world
that aren't made out of stone.

970
01:12:15,289 --> 01:12:16,789
There's something...

971
01:12:17,124 --> 01:12:18,541
...inside...

972
01:12:18,792 --> 01:12:20,752
...that they can't get to...

973
01:12:20,961 --> 01:12:22,378
...that they can't touch.

974
01:12:22,880 --> 01:12:24,297
That's yours.

975
01:12:25,841 --> 01:12:27,425
What are you talking about?

976
01:12:28,469 --> 01:12:32,096
Hope.

977
01:12:34,058 --> 01:12:36,059
Let me tell you something, my friend.

978
01:12:36,852 --> 01:12:39,145
Hope is a dangerous thing.

979
01:12:40,314 --> 01:12:42,648
Hope can drive a man insane.

980
01:12:43,400 --> 01:12:45,526
It's got no use on the inside.

981
01:12:45,736 --> 01:12:47,945
You'd better get used to that idea.

982
01:12:50,449 --> 01:12:51,949
Like Brooks did?

983
01:13:17,309 --> 01:13:18,309
Sit down.

984
01:13:23,649 --> 01:13:26,943
Says here that you've served
30 years of a life sentence.

985
01:13:28,112 --> 01:13:30,154
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

986
01:13:30,364 --> 01:13:31,614
Oh, yes, sir.

987
01:13:32,866 --> 01:13:34,200
Without a doubt.

988
01:13:35,369 --> 01:13:37,787
I can honestly say I'm a changed man.

989
01:13:39,790 --> 01:13:41,707
No danger to society here.

990
01:13:42,251 --> 01:13:43,793
God's honest truth.

991
01:13:46,338 --> 01:13:48,464
Absolutely rehabilitated.

992
01:13:58,434 --> 01:13:59,767
Thirty years.

993
01:14:01,728 --> 01:14:03,646
Jesus, when you say it like that...

994
01:14:04,523 --> 01:14:06,315
You wonder where it went.

995
01:14:08,735 --> 01:14:10,903
I wonder where 10 years went.

996
01:14:15,868 --> 01:14:16,909
Here.

997
01:14:17,369 --> 01:14:20,079
A little parole-rejection present.

998
01:14:21,373 --> 01:14:23,040
Go ahead and open it.

999
01:14:24,168 --> 01:14:26,210
Went through one of your competitors.

1000
01:14:26,378 --> 01:14:29,547
I hope you don't mind.
I wanted it to be a surprise.

1001
01:14:39,558 --> 01:14:41,058
It's very pretty.

1002
01:14:42,769 --> 01:14:43,978
Thank you.

1003
01:14:46,565 --> 01:14:48,024
You going to play it?

1004
01:14:52,571 --> 01:14:53,863
No.

1005
01:14:57,451 --> 01:14:58,868
Not right now.

1006
01:15:04,750 --> 01:15:07,835
[GUARDS SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

1007
01:15:16,553 --> 01:15:17,637
GUARD:
Roll in!

1008
01:15:53,840 --> 01:15:55,091
GUARD:
Lights out!

1009
01:16:29,668 --> 01:16:31,836
RED:
Andy was as good as his word.

1010
01:16:32,170 --> 01:16:34,964
He wrote two letters a week
instead of one.

1011
01:16:37,009 --> 01:16:41,137
In 1959, the state senate
finally clued in to the fact...

1012
01:16:41,346 --> 01:16:44,515
...they couldn't buy him off
with just a $200 check.

1013
01:16:44,683 --> 01:16:49,020
Appropriations Committee
voted an annual payment of $500...

1014
01:16:49,187 --> 01:16:51,105
...just to shut him up.

1015
01:16:51,315 --> 01:16:54,317
And you'd be amazed how far
Andy could stretch it.

1016
01:16:54,526 --> 01:16:57,445
He made deals with book clubs,
charity groups.

1017
01:16:57,654 --> 01:17:00,406
He bought remaindered books
by the pound...

1018
01:17:00,907 --> 01:17:02,450
"Treasure Island."

1019
01:17:02,993 --> 01:17:04,327
Robert Louis...

1020
01:17:04,536 --> 01:17:05,536
Stevenson.

1021
01:17:05,746 --> 01:17:07,163
Fiction, adventure.

1022
01:17:09,708 --> 01:17:10,750
What's next?

1023
01:17:10,917 --> 01:17:14,003
I got here Auto Repair...

1024
01:17:14,713 --> 01:17:15,880
...and Soap Carving.

1025
01:17:16,089 --> 01:17:19,342
Trade skills and hobbies.
Under "Educational," behind you.

1026
01:17:19,551 --> 01:17:21,385
"Count of Monte Crisco."

1027
01:17:21,887 --> 01:17:24,180
That's "Cristo," you dumb-shit.

1028
01:17:25,265 --> 01:17:26,265
By Alexandree...

1029
01:17:26,725 --> 01:17:28,017
...Dum-ass.

1030
01:17:28,352 --> 01:17:29,393
Dumb-ass.

1031
01:17:31,688 --> 01:17:32,730
Dumb-ass?

1032
01:17:35,651 --> 01:17:38,944
- Dumas. Know what that's about?
- Huh.

1033
01:17:39,905 --> 01:17:41,906
You'd like it. It's about a prison break.

1034
01:17:42,074 --> 01:17:45,951
We ought to file that
under "Educational" too, oughtn't we?

1035
01:17:46,828 --> 01:17:50,915
RED: The rest of us did our best
to pitch in when and where we could.

1036
01:17:51,500 --> 01:17:53,250
By the year Kennedy was shot...

1037
01:17:53,502 --> 01:17:58,005
...Andy had transformed a storage room
smelling of turpentine...

1038
01:17:58,298 --> 01:18:01,425
...into the best prison library
in New England...

1039
01:18:02,094 --> 01:18:05,054
...complete with a fine selection
of Hank Williams.

1040
01:18:05,222 --> 01:18:08,766
[SINGING HANK WILLIAMS'
"LOVE SICK BLUES"]

1041
01:18:12,437 --> 01:18:14,355
That was also when Warden Norton...

1042
01:18:14,564 --> 01:18:17,483
...instituted his famous
"Inside Out" program.

1043
01:18:17,943 --> 01:18:20,027
You may remember reading about it.

1044
01:18:20,278 --> 01:18:23,364
It made the papers
and got his picture in Look magazine.

1045
01:18:23,573 --> 01:18:24,907
It's no free ride...

1046
01:18:25,075 --> 01:18:28,285
...but rather a genuine
progressive advance...

1047
01:18:28,495 --> 01:18:30,996
...in corrections and rehabilitation.

1048
01:18:31,331 --> 01:18:33,874
Our inmates, properly supervised...

1049
01:18:34,084 --> 01:18:36,711
...will be put to work
outside these walls...

1050
01:18:36,920 --> 01:18:40,005
...performing all manner
of public service.

1051
01:18:40,173 --> 01:18:42,967
These men can learn the value
of an honest day's labor...

1052
01:18:43,176 --> 01:18:46,971
...while providing a valuable service
to the community...

1053
01:18:47,180 --> 01:18:51,892
...and at a bare minimum of expense
to Mr. And Mrs. John Q. Taxpayer.

1054
01:18:52,310 --> 01:18:54,645
RED:
Of course he didn't tell the press...

1055
01:18:54,855 --> 01:18:58,315
...that "bare minimum of expense"
is a fairly loose term.

1056
01:18:58,525 --> 01:19:01,569
There are 100 different ways
to skim off the top.

1057
01:19:01,778 --> 01:19:04,280
Men, materials, you name it.

1058
01:19:04,614 --> 01:19:07,491
And oh, my Lord,
how the money rolled in!

1059
01:19:07,701 --> 01:19:10,244
- You'll put me out of business.
- Ned.

1060
01:19:10,454 --> 01:19:14,874
With this pool of slave labor,
you can underbid any contractor in town.

1061
01:19:15,459 --> 01:19:18,419
We're providing
a valuable community service.

1062
01:19:18,628 --> 01:19:23,966
That's fine for the papers,
but I've got a family to feed. Sam.

1063
01:19:24,968 --> 01:19:26,510
We go back a long way, Sam.

1064
01:19:27,804 --> 01:19:32,725
I need this new highway contract.
I don't get it and I go under. That's a fact.

1065
01:19:33,643 --> 01:19:35,436
You have some of this fine pie...

1066
01:19:35,687 --> 01:19:39,023
...my missus made especially for you.
You think about that.

1067
01:19:47,282 --> 01:19:49,992
Ned, I wouldn't worry too much
about this contract.

1068
01:19:50,202 --> 01:19:53,287
It seems to me I already got my boys
committed elsewhere.

1069
01:19:55,248 --> 01:19:58,334
You be sure and thank Maisie
for this fine pie.

1070
01:19:59,419 --> 01:20:01,587
RED:
And behind every shady deal...

1071
01:20:01,922 --> 01:20:04,548
...behind every dollar earned...

1072
01:20:04,841 --> 01:20:07,885
...there was Andy, keeping the books.

1073
01:20:08,303 --> 01:20:09,553
Two deposits.

1074
01:20:09,805 --> 01:20:13,933
Maine National and New England First.
Night drops as always, sir.

1075
01:20:44,130 --> 01:20:48,467
Get my stuff to the laundry. Two suits
for dry-clean and a bag of whatnot.

1076
01:20:48,927 --> 01:20:51,846
If they over-starch my shirts again,
they'll hear from me.

1077
01:20:52,013 --> 01:20:54,014
- Yes, sir.
- How do I look?

1078
01:20:55,058 --> 01:20:57,560
- Very nice.
- Big charity to-do up Portland way.

1079
01:20:57,769 --> 01:20:59,270
- Governor will be there.
- Hmm.

1080
01:21:00,689 --> 01:21:02,147
You want the rest of this?

1081
01:21:03,483 --> 01:21:05,442
Woman can't bake worth shit.

1082
01:21:06,653 --> 01:21:07,987
Thank you, sir.

1083
01:21:10,824 --> 01:21:14,076
He's got his fingers
in a lot of pies, from what I hear.

1084
01:21:14,286 --> 01:21:19,123
He's got scams you haven't even
dreamed of. Kickbacks on his kickbacks.

1085
01:21:19,291 --> 01:21:21,667
A river of dirty money
running through here.

1086
01:21:21,877 --> 01:21:25,713
Sooner or later, he'll have to
explain where it came from.

1087
01:21:25,922 --> 01:21:27,673
That's where I come in.

1088
01:21:28,300 --> 01:21:30,593
I channel it. Filter it. Funnel it.

1089
01:21:30,802 --> 01:21:33,637
Stocks, securities,
tax-free municipals.

1090
01:21:33,972 --> 01:21:37,474
I send it out into the real world,
and when it comes back...

1091
01:21:37,684 --> 01:21:40,644
- Clean as a virgin's honeypot, huh?
- Cleaner.

1092
01:21:41,271 --> 01:21:44,857
By the time Norton retires,
I'll have made him a millionaire.

1093
01:21:47,193 --> 01:21:51,530
If they ever catch on, he'll wind up
in here wearing a number himself.

1094
01:21:51,823 --> 01:21:54,491
I thought you had
more faith in me than that.

1095
01:21:54,701 --> 01:21:57,745
I know you're good,
but all that paper leaves a trail.

1096
01:21:58,121 --> 01:21:59,955
Now anybody gets curious...

1097
01:22:00,123 --> 01:22:02,541
FBI, IRS, whatever.

1098
01:22:03,001 --> 01:22:04,293
- It'll lead to somebody.

1099
01:22:04,502 --> 01:22:08,339
Sure it is, but not to me,
and certainly not to the warden.

1100
01:22:12,719 --> 01:22:13,719
All right, who?

1101
01:22:13,887 --> 01:22:15,512
Randall Stevens.

1102
01:22:16,014 --> 01:22:17,014
Who?

1103
01:22:17,182 --> 01:22:19,183
The "silent" silent partner.

1104
01:22:19,392 --> 01:22:22,478
He's the guilty one,
the man with the bank accounts.

1105
01:22:22,687 --> 01:22:24,855
It's where the filtering
process starts.

1106
01:22:25,023 --> 01:22:27,900
They trace anything,
it'll just lead to him.

1107
01:22:28,526 --> 01:22:29,735
But who is he?

1108
01:22:29,945 --> 01:22:33,906
He's a phantom, an apparition.
Second cousin to Harvey the Rabbit.

1109
01:22:35,033 --> 01:22:36,200
I conjured him...

1110
01:22:36,368 --> 01:22:37,743
...out of thin air.

1111
01:22:38,536 --> 01:22:41,288
He doesn't exist, except on paper.

1112
01:22:44,376 --> 01:22:46,710
Andy, you can't just make a person up.

1113
01:22:46,920 --> 01:22:50,047
Sure you can,
if you know how the system works.

1114
01:22:50,548 --> 01:22:53,384
It's amazing what you
can accomplish by mail.

1115
01:22:53,718 --> 01:22:56,345
Mr. Stevens has a birth certificate...

1116
01:22:56,554 --> 01:22:58,681
...driver's license, Social Security number.

1117
01:22:58,932 --> 01:22:59,932
You're shitting me.

1118
01:23:00,100 --> 01:23:03,519
If they trace any accounts,
they'll wind up chasing...

1119
01:23:03,728 --> 01:23:05,437
...a figment of my imagination.

1120
01:23:05,647 --> 01:23:07,648
Well, I'll be damned!

1121
01:23:08,984 --> 01:23:10,734
Did I say you were good?

1122
01:23:11,069 --> 01:23:12,736
Shit, you are Rembrandt.

1123
01:23:13,446 --> 01:23:15,197
The funny thing is...

1124
01:23:15,407 --> 01:23:19,493
...on the outside, I was an honest man,
straight as an arrow.

1125
01:23:19,911 --> 01:23:22,246
I had to come to prison to be a crook.

1126
01:23:23,206 --> 01:23:26,458
[CHUCKLING]

1127
01:23:31,089 --> 01:23:32,423
Ever bother you?

1128
01:23:33,842 --> 01:23:36,927
I don't run the scams.
I just process the profits.

1129
01:23:37,178 --> 01:23:39,179
A fine line, maybe...

1130
01:23:39,764 --> 01:23:41,807
...but I also built that library...

1131
01:23:42,017 --> 01:23:45,060
...and used it to help guys
get their high school diploma.

1132
01:23:45,270 --> 01:23:47,479
Why do you think
he lets me do all that?

1133
01:23:47,689 --> 01:23:49,898
Keep you happy and doing the laundry.

1134
01:23:50,108 --> 01:23:51,567
Money instead of sheets.

1135
01:23:51,943 --> 01:23:54,486
Well, I work cheap.
That's the tradeoff.

1136
01:23:54,654 --> 01:23:57,990
[SIREN WAILING]

1137
01:24:11,796 --> 01:24:14,423
RED: Tommy Williams came
to Shawshank in 1965...

1138
01:24:14,632 --> 01:24:16,884
...on a two-year stretch for B and E.

1139
01:24:17,135 --> 01:24:19,470
That's breaking and entering to you.

1140
01:24:19,721 --> 01:24:23,974
Cops caught him sneaking TV sets
out the back door of a JC Penney.

1141
01:24:24,392 --> 01:24:25,684
Young punk.

1142
01:24:25,894 --> 01:24:27,519
Mr. Rock 'n' Roll...

1143
01:24:27,729 --> 01:24:29,271
...cocky as hell.

1144
01:24:29,481 --> 01:24:31,857
Come on, old boys.
Moving like molasses!

1145
01:24:32,108 --> 01:24:33,859
Making me look bad.

1146
01:24:34,069 --> 01:24:35,861
RED:
We liked him immediately.

1147
01:24:36,112 --> 01:24:39,823
I'm backing out the door
and I got the TV like this.

1148
01:24:40,158 --> 01:24:43,786
A big old thing. I couldn't see shit.
Then I hear this voice.

1149
01:24:44,412 --> 01:24:46,371
"Freeze, kid, hands in the air."

1150
01:24:46,581 --> 01:24:51,043
I was standing there, holding onto
that TV. Finally the voice says:

1151
01:24:51,252 --> 01:24:55,047
"You hear what I said, boy?"
I say, "Yes, sir. I sure did.

1152
01:24:55,256 --> 01:24:58,717
But if I drop this, you get me
on destruction of property too."

1153
01:24:58,927 --> 01:25:01,386
[LAUGHING]

1154
01:25:03,181 --> 01:25:05,849
Hey, you done some stretch
in Cashman, right?

1155
01:25:06,017 --> 01:25:09,978
Yeah, that was an easy piece of time,
let me tell you.

1156
01:25:10,230 --> 01:25:12,189
Weekend furloughs. Work programs.

1157
01:25:12,857 --> 01:25:14,149
Not like here.

1158
01:25:14,317 --> 01:25:16,068
Sounds like you done time all over.

1159
01:25:16,528 --> 01:25:18,904
Yeah, I've been in and out since I was 13.

1160
01:25:19,114 --> 01:25:21,323
You name it, chances are I've been there.

1161
01:25:21,533 --> 01:25:24,201
Perhaps you should try a new profession.

1162
01:25:25,620 --> 01:25:27,204
What I mean is...

1163
01:25:27,539 --> 01:25:30,499
...you're not a very good thief.
You should try something else.

1164
01:25:31,209 --> 01:25:34,419
Yeah, what the hell
you know about it, Capone?

1165
01:25:34,838 --> 01:25:36,421
What are you in for?

1166
01:25:36,714 --> 01:25:37,714
Me?

1167
01:25:40,135 --> 01:25:41,802
A lawyer fucked me.

1168
01:25:45,723 --> 01:25:48,684
Everybody's innocent in here.
Don't you know that?

1169
01:25:56,568 --> 01:26:00,988
RED: As it turned out, Tommy had himself
a young wife and a new baby girl.

1170
01:26:01,573 --> 01:26:03,699
Maybe he thought of them
on the streets...

1171
01:26:03,908 --> 01:26:06,410
...or his child growing up
not knowing her daddy.

1172
01:26:06,703 --> 01:26:08,078
Whatever it was...

1173
01:26:08,413 --> 01:26:10,831
...something lit a fire
under that boy's ass.

1174
01:26:14,669 --> 01:26:17,546
Thought I might try for
my high school equivalency.

1175
01:26:17,755 --> 01:26:20,257
Hear you helped
a couple of fellas with that.

1176
01:26:21,593 --> 01:26:23,844
I don't waste time with losers, Tommy.

1177
01:26:25,263 --> 01:26:27,764
I ain't no goddamn loser.

1178
01:26:29,475 --> 01:26:31,310
- You mean that?
- Yeah.

1179
01:26:32,979 --> 01:26:34,438
You really mean that?

1180
01:26:35,440 --> 01:26:36,815
Yes, sir, I do.

1181
01:26:37,025 --> 01:26:38,984
Good. Because if we do this...

1182
01:26:39,194 --> 01:26:43,155
...we do it all the way,
a hundred percent, nothing half-assed.

1183
01:26:43,406 --> 01:26:45,199
Thing is, see...

1184
01:26:46,451 --> 01:26:47,993
...I don't read so good.

1185
01:26:49,162 --> 01:26:50,287
"Well."

1186
01:26:52,290 --> 01:26:53,999
You don't read...

1187
01:26:54,250 --> 01:26:55,792
...so well.

1188
01:26:58,129 --> 01:26:59,630
We'll get to that.

1189
01:27:04,052 --> 01:27:06,178
RED:
So Andy took Tommy under his wing.

1190
01:27:06,387 --> 01:27:09,014
Started walking him through his ABC's.

1191
01:27:11,142 --> 01:27:13,352
Tommy took to it pretty well too.

1192
01:27:13,645 --> 01:27:16,396
Boy found brains he never knew he had.

1193
01:27:18,733 --> 01:27:22,152
Before long, Andy started him
on his course requirements.

1194
01:27:22,362 --> 01:27:24,029
He really liked the kid.

1195
01:27:24,239 --> 01:27:27,824
Gave him a thrill to help a youngster
crawl off the shit heap.

1196
01:27:28,326 --> 01:27:30,577
But that wasn't the only reason.

1197
01:27:31,287 --> 01:27:33,497
Prison time is slow time.

1198
01:27:33,957 --> 01:27:36,541
So you do what you can to keep going.

1199
01:27:36,876 --> 01:27:38,961
Some fellas collect stamps.

1200
01:27:39,337 --> 01:27:41,838
Others build matchstick houses.

1201
01:27:42,423 --> 01:27:45,092
Andy built a library.

1202
01:27:45,593 --> 01:27:47,511
Now he needed a new project.

1203
01:27:48,388 --> 01:27:49,888
Tommy was it.

1204
01:27:50,515 --> 01:27:54,518
It was the same reason he spent years
shaping and polishing those rocks.

1205
01:27:55,061 --> 01:27:58,313
The same reason he hung
his fantasy girlies on the wall.

1206
01:27:59,190 --> 01:28:00,482
In prison...

1207
01:28:00,733 --> 01:28:04,486
...a man will do most anything
to keep his mind occupied.

1208
01:28:05,238 --> 01:28:10,117
By 1966, right about the time Tommy
was getting ready to take his exams...

1209
01:28:10,368 --> 01:28:12,536
...it was lovely Raquel.

1210
01:28:13,079 --> 01:28:15,205
[CLOCK TICKING]

1211
01:28:29,095 --> 01:28:30,095
Time.

1212
01:28:36,144 --> 01:28:37,394
Well?

1213
01:28:38,730 --> 01:28:40,897
Well, it's for shit.

1214
01:28:41,399 --> 01:28:44,234
I wasted a whole year
of my time with this bullshit.

1215
01:28:44,402 --> 01:28:45,902
It's probably not that bad.

1216
01:28:46,112 --> 01:28:50,365
Yeah, I didn't get a thing right.
It might as well have been in Chinese.

1217
01:28:50,575 --> 01:28:52,284
Let's see how the score comes out.

1218
01:28:52,493 --> 01:28:55,454
Yeah, well, I'll tell you
how the goddamn score comes out.

1219
01:28:57,415 --> 01:28:58,749
Two points, right there!

1220
01:28:58,958 --> 01:29:00,542
There's your goddamn score!

1221
01:29:00,752 --> 01:29:04,463
Goddamn cats crawling up trees,
5 times 5 is 25...

1222
01:29:05,423 --> 01:29:07,049
Fuck this place!

1223
01:29:07,258 --> 01:29:08,425
Fuck it!

1224
01:29:27,570 --> 01:29:28,820
I feel bad.

1225
01:29:29,030 --> 01:29:30,238
I let him down.

1226
01:29:30,448 --> 01:29:32,157
That's crap, kid.

1227
01:29:32,367 --> 01:29:33,700
He's proud of you.

1228
01:29:34,035 --> 01:29:36,912
We're old friends,
I know him as good as anybody.

1229
01:29:37,121 --> 01:29:38,663
Smart fellow, ain't he?

1230
01:29:38,873 --> 01:29:42,000
Smart as they come.
He was a banker on the outside.

