01:47:29,776 --> 01:47:31,485
I'm really worried about him.

1482
01:47:31,862 --> 01:47:33,320
Let's keep an eye on him.

1483
01:47:33,530 --> 01:47:36,782
That's fine during the day,
but at night he's all alone.

1484
01:47:38,201 --> 01:47:39,368
Oh, Lord.

1485
01:47:40,704 --> 01:47:42,288
What?

1486
01:47:43,039 --> 01:47:45,791
Andy come down
to the loading dock today.

1487
01:47:46,001 --> 01:47:48,085
He asked me for a length of rope.

1488
01:47:48,295 --> 01:47:51,005
- Rope?
- Six feet long.

1489
01:47:51,214 --> 01:47:52,590
And you gave it to him.

1490
01:47:53,467 --> 01:47:55,259
Sure I did. Why wouldn't I?

1491
01:47:55,469 --> 01:47:57,052
Jesus! Heywood.

1492
01:47:57,637 --> 01:47:59,597
How was I supposed to know?

1493
01:47:59,806 --> 01:48:01,390
Remember Brooks Hatlen?

1494
01:48:01,600 --> 01:48:05,311
No. Andy would never do that.

1495
01:48:05,896 --> 01:48:07,354
Never.

1496
01:48:09,065 --> 01:48:10,399
I don't know.

1497
01:48:13,236 --> 01:48:15,237
Every man has his breaking point.

1498
01:48:17,574 --> 01:48:19,867
Lickety-split. Want to get home.

1499
01:48:20,160 --> 01:48:21,911
Just about finished, sir.

1500
01:48:39,054 --> 01:48:40,679
Three deposits tonight.

1501
01:48:48,647 --> 01:48:50,564
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1502
01:48:50,774 --> 01:48:52,399
And shine my shoes.

1503
01:48:52,609 --> 01:48:55,528
- I want them looking like mirrors.
- Yes, sir.

1504
01:49:01,034 --> 01:49:02,493
It's good having you back, Andy.

1505
01:49:03,453 --> 01:49:05,287
Place wasn't the same without you.

1506
01:49:07,624 --> 01:49:10,459
[NORTON WHISTLING]

1507
01:49:52,168 --> 01:49:53,544
GUARD:
Lights out!

1508
01:50:26,077 --> 01:50:28,621
RED:
I've had some long nights in the stir.

1509
01:50:29,164 --> 01:50:31,832
Alone in the dark
with nothing but your thoughts...

1510
01:50:32,042 --> 01:50:34,710
...time can draw out like a blade.

1511
01:50:40,050 --> 01:50:43,052
That was the longest night of my life.

1512
01:50:52,562 --> 01:50:55,105
[HORN BUZZING]

1513
01:50:58,902 --> 01:51:00,069
GUARD 1:
Give me a count!

1514
01:51:04,574 --> 01:51:07,409
GUARD 2:
Tier 3 south, clear!

1515
01:51:10,538 --> 01:51:13,707
Man missing on tier 2, cell 245!

1516
01:51:13,917 --> 01:51:14,958
Dufresne!

1517
01:51:15,502 --> 01:51:17,920
Come out. You're holding up the show!

1518
01:51:21,091 --> 01:51:24,468
Don't make me come down
or I'll thump your skull for you!

1519
01:51:32,060 --> 01:51:35,896
Damn it, you're putting me behind!
I got a schedule to keep.

1520
01:51:36,106 --> 01:51:39,400
You'd better be sick or dead in there.
I shit you not!

1521
01:51:39,609 --> 01:51:40,943
You hear me?

1522
01:51:47,033 --> 01:51:49,118
Oh, my Holy God.

1523
01:52:01,256 --> 01:52:04,299
[SIREN WAILING]

1524
01:52:06,136 --> 01:52:08,679
I want every man
on this cellblock questioned.

1525
01:52:09,139 --> 01:52:11,682
- Start with that friend of his.
- Who?

1526
01:52:11,850 --> 01:52:13,267
Him.

1527
01:52:14,269 --> 01:52:15,811
HADLEY:
Open 237.

1528
01:52:19,315 --> 01:52:22,985
What do you mean, "He just wasn't here"?
Don't say that to me.

1529
01:52:23,862 --> 01:52:26,447
- Don't say that to me again.
- But, sir, he wasn't.

1530
01:52:26,656 --> 01:52:30,159
I can see that, Haig! Think I'm blind?

1531
01:52:30,827 --> 01:52:32,411
Is that what you're saying?

1532
01:52:32,579 --> 01:52:35,080
- Am I blind, Haig?
- No, sir!

1533
01:52:35,999 --> 01:52:38,500
What about you. You blind?

1534
01:52:39,002 --> 01:52:41,336
- Tell me what this is.
- Last night's count.

1535
01:52:41,504 --> 01:52:45,048
Uh-huh. You see Dufresne's name there?
I sure do. Right there.

1536
01:52:45,258 --> 01:52:46,592
"Dufresne."

1537
01:52:48,261 --> 01:52:51,013
He was in his cell at lights out.

1538
01:52:51,181 --> 01:52:54,099
Stands to reason he'd still be here
in the morning.

1539
01:52:54,434 --> 01:52:56,059
I want him found.

1540
01:52:56,269 --> 01:52:59,730
Not tomorrow, not after breakfast. Now!

1541
01:52:59,981 --> 01:53:01,190
Yes, sir.

1542
01:53:02,192 --> 01:53:05,986
Let's go. Move your butts. Move it!

1543
01:53:07,864 --> 01:53:08,864
Stand.

1544
01:53:10,283 --> 01:53:11,700
Well?

1545
01:53:14,788 --> 01:53:15,829
Well, what?

1546
01:53:15,997 --> 01:53:19,458
I see you two all the time.
You're thick as thieves, you are.

1547
01:53:20,543 --> 01:53:22,044
He must have said something.

1548
01:53:22,754 --> 01:53:25,672
No, sir, warden. Not a word.

1549
01:53:27,467 --> 01:53:30,052
Lord, it's a miracle!

1550
01:53:30,637 --> 01:53:33,222
Man vanished like a fart in the wind.

1551
01:53:33,890 --> 01:53:35,057
Nothing left...

1552
01:53:35,892 --> 01:53:38,602
...but some damn rocks
on a windowsill.

1553
01:53:38,812 --> 01:53:41,563
And that cupcake on the wall.
Let's ask her.

1554
01:53:41,731 --> 01:53:43,065
Maybe she knows.

1555
01:53:43,233 --> 01:53:46,443
What say there, fuzzy-britches?
Feel like talking?

1556
01:53:46,778 --> 01:53:49,238
Oh, guess not.

1557
01:53:49,781 --> 01:53:51,990
Why should she be any different?

1558
01:53:53,076 --> 01:53:54,743
This is a conspiracy.

1559
01:53:55,370 --> 01:53:57,079
That's what this is.

1560
01:53:57,789 --> 01:54:01,542
One big, damn conspiracy!

1561
01:54:01,793 --> 01:54:03,794
And everyone's in on it!

1562
01:54:04,420 --> 01:54:05,587
Including her!

1563
01:54:40,623 --> 01:54:42,332
RED:
In 1966...

1564
01:54:42,542 --> 01:54:44,960
...Andy Dufresne escaped...

1565
01:54:45,128 --> 01:54:46,712
...from Shawshank Prison.

1566
01:54:48,965 --> 01:54:51,508
All they found of him
was a muddy set of prison clothes...

1567
01:54:52,135 --> 01:54:53,677
...a bar of soap...

1568
01:54:53,887 --> 01:54:55,470
...and an old rock hammer...

1569
01:54:55,638 --> 01:54:58,140
...damn near worn down to the nub.

1570
01:55:02,645 --> 01:55:07,399
I remember thinking it would take a man
600 years to tunnel through the wall with it.

1571
01:55:08,026 --> 01:55:10,652
Old Andy did it in less than 20.

1572
01:55:28,963 --> 01:55:31,256
Oh, Andy loved geology.

1573
01:55:32,008 --> 01:55:35,177
I imagine it appealed to
his meticulous nature.

1574
01:55:35,595 --> 01:55:37,429
An ice age here...

1575
01:55:37,847 --> 01:55:40,349
...million years
of mountain-building there.

1576
01:55:41,351 --> 01:55:44,186
Geology is the study
of pressure and time.

1577
01:55:45,021 --> 01:55:47,022
That's all it takes, really.

1578
01:55:47,774 --> 01:55:49,066
Pressure...

1579
01:55:49,525 --> 01:55:51,026
...and time.

1580
01:55:52,111 --> 01:55:54,196
That and a big goddamn poster.

1581
01:55:55,657 --> 01:55:57,824
[MAN COUGHING]

1582
01:55:57,992 --> 01:55:59,159
Like I said...

1583
01:55:59,661 --> 01:56:03,664
...in prison, a man will do anything
to keep his mind occupied.

1584
01:56:06,459 --> 01:56:11,254
Seems Andy's favorite hobby was toting
his wall out into the exercise yard...

1585
01:56:11,798 --> 01:56:13,715
...a handful at a time.

1586
01:56:15,051 --> 01:56:17,094
I guess after Tommy was killed...

1587
01:56:17,303 --> 01:56:20,263
...Andy decided
he'd been here just about long enough.

1588
01:56:20,473 --> 01:56:23,058
Lickety-split. Want to get home.

1589
01:56:23,768 --> 01:56:25,811
I'm just about finished, sir.

1590
01:56:47,250 --> 01:56:49,209
Three deposits tonight.

1591
01:56:56,509 --> 01:56:58,802
RED:
Andy did like he was told.

1592
01:56:59,012 --> 01:57:02,514
Buffed those shoes
to a high mirror-shine.

1593
01:57:06,185 --> 01:57:08,478
The guards simply didn't notice.

1594
01:57:08,771 --> 01:57:10,272
Neither did I.

1595
01:57:10,440 --> 01:57:11,982
I mean, seriously...

1596
01:57:12,191 --> 01:57:15,193
...how often do you really look
at a man's shoes?

1597
01:59:18,734 --> 01:59:21,903
Andy crawled to freedom
through 500 yards...

1598
01:59:22,155 --> 01:59:25,490
...of shit-smelling foulness
I can't even imagine.

1599
01:59:26,492 --> 01:59:28,827
Or maybe I just don't want to.

1600
01:59:33,249 --> 01:59:35,584
Five hundred yards.

1601
01:59:36,085 --> 01:59:39,171
That's the length
of five football fields.

1602
01:59:39,797 --> 01:59:42,382
Just shy of half a mile.

1603
02:00:31,891 --> 02:00:34,809
[LAUGHING]

1604
02:00:37,605 --> 02:00:42,192
The next morning, right about the time
Raquel was spilling her little secret...

1605
02:00:42,485 --> 02:00:45,320
...a man nobody ever
laid eyes on before...

1606
02:00:45,571 --> 02:00:48,156
...strolled into
the Maine National Bank.

1607
02:00:48,741 --> 02:00:51,910
Until that moment, he didn't exist.

1608
02:00:52,495 --> 02:00:54,829
- Except on paper.
- May I help you?

1609
02:00:55,248 --> 02:00:57,165
He had all the proper ID...

1610
02:00:57,375 --> 02:01:01,086
Driver's license, birth certificate,
Social Security card.

1611
02:01:01,504 --> 02:01:04,047
- And the signature
was a spot-on match.

1612
02:01:04,257 --> 02:01:07,342
I must say I'm sorry
to be losing your business.

1613
02:01:07,551 --> 02:01:09,302
I hope you'll enjoy living abroad.

1614
02:01:10,096 --> 02:01:11,680
Thank you.

1615
02:01:11,847 --> 02:01:13,014
I'm sure I will.

1616
02:01:13,933 --> 02:01:17,269
Here's your cashier's check, sir.
Will there be anything else?

1617
02:01:17,478 --> 02:01:18,478
Please.

1618
02:01:19,021 --> 02:01:21,523
Would you add this
to your outgoing mail?

1619
02:01:22,024 --> 02:01:23,566
I'd be happy to.

1620
02:01:25,027 --> 02:01:26,361
Good day, sir.

1621
02:01:27,321 --> 02:01:31,741
RED: Mr. Stevens visited nearly
a dozen banks in the Portland area.

1622
02:01:32,201 --> 02:01:33,827
All told, he blew town...

1623
02:01:34,036 --> 02:01:38,873
...with better than $370,000
of Warden Norton's money.

1624
02:01:39,542 --> 02:01:42,335
Severance pay for 19 years.

1625
02:01:42,503 --> 02:01:44,045
[PHONE RINGING]

1626
02:01:49,552 --> 02:01:51,761
WOMAN:
Good morning, Portland Daily Bugle.

1627
02:01:58,394 --> 02:02:00,895
[SIREN WAILING]

1628
02:02:44,607 --> 02:02:47,567
Byron Hadley?
You have the right to remain silent.

1629
02:02:47,818 --> 02:02:52,280
If you give up this right, anything you
say can be held against you in court.

1630
02:02:52,698 --> 02:02:57,160
RED: I wasn't there to see it, but I hear
Byron Hadley sobbed like a little girl...

1631
02:02:57,370 --> 02:02:58,870
...when they took him away.

1632
02:03:04,752 --> 02:03:08,129
Norton had no intention
of going that quietly.

1633
02:03:24,105 --> 02:03:25,480
Samuel Norton.

1634
02:03:25,648 --> 02:03:27,649
We have a warrant for your arrest.
Open up.

1635
02:03:27,817 --> 02:03:29,567
[KNOCKING]

1636
02:03:31,278 --> 02:03:34,280
Norton. Open the door.

1637
02:03:34,448 --> 02:03:35,698
I'm not sure which key.

1638
02:03:38,494 --> 02:03:40,412
Norton!

1639
02:03:45,835 --> 02:03:47,794
Make it easy on yourself, Norton!

1640
02:03:59,306 --> 02:04:02,767
RED: I like to think the last thing
that went through his head...

1641
02:04:02,977 --> 02:04:04,561
...other than that bullet...

1642
02:04:04,770 --> 02:04:09,190
...was to wonder how the hell
Andy Dufresne ever got the best of him.

1643
02:04:11,694 --> 02:04:15,196
Not long after the warden
deprived us of his company...

1644
02:04:15,448 --> 02:04:17,532
...I got a postcard in the mail.

1645
02:04:18,993 --> 02:04:21,828
It was blank, but the postmark said...

1646
02:04:22,037 --> 02:04:24,164
...Fort Hancock, Texas.

1647
02:04:24,707 --> 02:04:26,040
Fort Hancock...

1648
02:04:26,333 --> 02:04:28,042
...right on the border.

1649
02:04:28,461 --> 02:04:30,462
That's where Andy crossed.

1650
02:04:31,046 --> 02:04:35,175
When I picture him heading south
in his own car with the top down...

1651
02:04:35,509 --> 02:04:37,719
...it always makes me laugh.

1652
02:04:39,555 --> 02:04:41,139
Andy Dufresne...

1653
02:04:41,515 --> 02:04:43,558
...who crawled through
a river of shit...

1654
02:04:43,726 --> 02:04:46,144
...and came out clean
on the other side.

1655
02:04:46,979 --> 02:04:48,354
Andy Dufresne...

1656
02:04:49,148 --> 02:04:50,732
...headed for the Pacific.

1657
02:04:53,736 --> 02:04:55,904
Hadley's got him
by the throat, right?

1658
02:04:56,071 --> 02:04:59,908
He says, "I believe this boy's
about to have himself an accident."

1659
02:05:00,075 --> 02:05:02,952
RED: Those of us who knew him best
talk about him often.

1660
02:05:03,621 --> 02:05:05,330
I swear, the stuff he pulled...

1661
02:05:05,539 --> 02:05:08,500
"My friends could use
a couple of beers."

1662
02:05:08,834 --> 02:05:10,502
And he got it!

1663
02:05:11,754 --> 02:05:14,130
RED:
Sometimes it makes me sad, though...

1664
02:05:14,423 --> 02:05:15,840
...Andy being gone.

1665
02:05:16,550 --> 02:05:20,678
I have to remind myself that
some birds aren't meant to be caged.

1666
02:05:21,138 --> 02:05:23,223
Their feathers are just too bright.

1667
02:05:24,934 --> 02:05:26,643
And when they fly away...

1668
02:05:27,102 --> 02:05:31,481
...the part of you that knows it was
a sin to lock them up does rejoice.

1669
02:05:32,566 --> 02:05:33,816
But still...

1670
02:05:34,276 --> 02:05:38,613
...the place you live in is that much
more drab and empty that they're gone.

1671
02:05:42,826 --> 02:05:45,203
I guess I just miss my friend.

1672
02:06:09,645 --> 02:06:10,812
Please sit down.

1673
02:06:16,652 --> 02:06:18,236
Ellis Boyd Redding...

1674
02:06:18,779 --> 02:06:22,031
...your files say you've served
40 years of a life sentence.

1675
02:06:22,825 --> 02:06:24,993
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

1676
02:06:26,829 --> 02:06:28,413
Rehabilitated?

1677
02:06:30,457 --> 02:06:32,333
Well, now, let me see.

1678
02:06:33,335 --> 02:06:35,670
I don't have any idea what that means.

1679
02:06:37,798 --> 02:06:40,049
It means you're ready
to rejoin society...

1680
02:06:40,634 --> 02:06:42,969
I know what you think it means, sonny.

1681
02:06:45,139 --> 02:06:47,140
To me it's just a made-up word.

1682
02:06:48,475 --> 02:06:50,810
A politician's word so that...

1683
02:06:51,228 --> 02:06:54,772
...young fellas like yourself
can wear a suit and a tie...

1684
02:06:55,232 --> 02:06:56,858
...and have a job.

1685
02:06:58,819 --> 02:07:00,903
What do you really want to know?

1686
02:07:01,697 --> 02:07:03,656
Am I sorry for what I did?

1687
02:07:04,074 --> 02:07:05,366
Well, are you?

1688
02:07:07,161 --> 02:07:09,996
There's not a day goes by
I don't feel regret.

1689
02:07:11,373 --> 02:07:14,834
Not because I'm in here
or because you think I should.

1690
02:07:18,297 --> 02:07:20,882
I look back on the way I was then...

1691
02:07:23,010 --> 02:07:24,344
...a young...

1692
02:07:25,262 --> 02:07:28,765
...stupid kid who committed
that terrible crime.

1693
02:07:31,769 --> 02:07:33,478
I want to talk to him.

1694
02:07:35,397 --> 02:07:37,899
I want to try
and talk some sense to him.

1695
02:07:38,609 --> 02:07:40,568
Tell him the way things are.

1696
02:07:42,655 --> 02:07:44,072
But I can't.

1697
02:07:46,283 --> 02:07:48,284
That kid's long gone...

1698
02:07:49,495 --> 02:07:52,246
...and this old man is all that's left.

1699
02:07:53,666 --> 02:07:55,124
I got to live with that.

1700
02:07:56,502 --> 02:07:58,211
Rehabilitated?

1701
02:07:58,587 --> 02:08:00,421
It's just a bullshit word.

1702
02:08:01,340 --> 02:08:06,094
So you go on and stamp your forms,
sonny, and stop wasting my time.

1703
02:08:07,346 --> 02:08:09,597
Because to tell you the truth...

1704
02:08:09,932 --> 02:08:11,933
...I don't give a shit.

1705
02:09:38,479 --> 02:09:39,854
Here you go, miss.

1706
02:09:42,816 --> 02:09:43,858
Restroom break, boss?

1707
02:09:49,656 --> 02:09:54,202
You don't need to ask me every time you
need to go take a piss. Just go. Understand?

1708
02:09:55,204 --> 02:09:56,829
Yes, sir.

1709
02:10:07,216 --> 02:10:10,301
RED: Forty years I've been asking
permission to piss.

1710
02:10:11,136 --> 02:10:14,138
I can't squeeze a drop without say-so.

1711
02:10:17,643 --> 02:10:19,811
There's a harsh truth to face.

1712
02:10:21,480 --> 02:10:24,398
No way I'm going to make it
on the outside.

1713
02:10:32,241 --> 02:10:35,952
All I do anymore is think of ways
to break my parole...

1714
02:10:36,745 --> 02:10:39,247
...so maybe they'd send me back.

1715
02:10:44,419 --> 02:10:46,879
Terrible thing, to live in fear.

1716
02:10:47,756 --> 02:10:49,423
Brooks Hatlen knew it.

1717
02:10:49,633 --> 02:10:51,592
Knew it all too well.

1718
02:10:53,178 --> 02:10:56,597
All I want is to be back
where things make sense.

1719
02:10:57,015 --> 02:10:59,767
Where I won't have to be afraid
all the time.

1720
02:11:01,770 --> 02:11:04,105
Only one thing stops me.

1721
02:11:05,566 --> 02:11:07,942
A promise I made to Andy.

1722
02:11:28,463 --> 02:11:29,797
MAN:
There it is.

1723
02:11:40,225 --> 02:11:41,893
RED:
Much obliged, sir.

1724
02:15:21,196 --> 02:15:22,488
ANDY:
Dear Red:

1725
02:15:22,697 --> 02:15:25,199
If you're reading this,
you've gotten out...

1726
02:15:25,367 --> 02:15:29,537
...and if you've come this far,
maybe you're willing to come a little further.

1727
02:15:29,704 --> 02:15:32,206
You remember the name
of the town, don't you?

1728
02:15:34,501 --> 02:15:36,001
Zihuatanejo.

1729
02:15:37,629 --> 02:15:41,215
ANDY: I could use a good man
to help me get my project on wheels.

1730
02:15:41,716 --> 02:15:45,261
I'll keep an eye out for you,
and the chessboard ready.

1731
02:15:46,054 --> 02:15:47,471
Remember, Red...

1732
02:15:47,806 --> 02:15:49,890
...hope is a good thing...

1733
02:15:50,100 --> 02:15:52,101
...maybe the best of things.

1734
02:15:52,310 --> 02:15:54,478
And no good thing ever dies.

1735
02:15:55,021 --> 02:15:57,898
I will be hoping
that this letter finds you...

1736
02:15:58,066 --> 02:15:59,817
...and finds you well.

1737
02:16:00,318 --> 02:16:01,569
Your friend...

1738
02:16:01,736 --> 02:16:02,903
...Andy.

1739
02:16:36,771 --> 02:16:38,480
RED:
"Get busy living...

1740
02:16:38,690 --> 02:16:40,608
...or get busy dying."

1741
02:16:43,278 --> 02:16:45,446
That's goddamn right.

1742
02:16:50,702 --> 02:16:52,828
For the second time in my life...

1743
02:16:53,079 --> 02:16:55,623
...I'm guilty of committing a crime.

1744
02:16:56,708 --> 02:16:58,626
Parole violation.

1745
02:16:59,294 --> 02:17:02,963
Of course, I doubt they'll toss up
any roadblocks for that.

1746
02:17:03,632 --> 02:17:05,674
Not for an old crook like me.

1747
02:17:05,884 --> 02:17:07,927
Fort Hancock, Texas, please.

1748
02:17:11,598 --> 02:17:16,310
RED: I find I'm so excited I can barely
sit still or hold a thought in my head.

1749
02:17:16,770 --> 02:17:20,105
I think it's the excitement
only a free man can feel.

1750
02:17:20,315 --> 02:17:22,816
A free man at the start
of a long journey...

1751
02:17:22,984 --> 02:17:25,611
...whose conclusion is uncertain.

1752
02:17:28,615 --> 02:17:31,283
I hope I can make it across the border.

1753
02:17:32,786 --> 02:17:35,829
I hope to see my friend
and shake his hand.

1754
02:17:37,666 --> 02:17:41,752
I hope the Pacific is as blue
as it has been in my dreams.

1755
02:17:43,588 --> 02:17:44,797
I hope.